'git checkout <branch>' switches to the new branch
'git checkout -b <branch>' combines branch creation and checkout
'git checkout <branch>' updates the files in the workspace
Conflicts* in the workspace will prevent the checkout
'git show [<ref>]' looks at the changes introduced by the commit
It is a comparison between <ref> and its parent*
Also provides information about the commit (author, date, commit message)
'git reset' leads to loss of history and/or loss of local changes.
Be very careful when using it!
'git reset' is short-hand for 'git reset HEAD'
No history is lost when resetting to HEAD.
The old commit is forgotten and a new one is created!
